status_message:
We pulled out the best for you. Here's what the pope had to say to Congress on:

INEQUALITY
"A political society endures when it seeks, as a vocation, to satisfy common needs by stimulating the growth of all its members, especially those in situations of greater vulnerability or risk."

IMMIGRATION
"We, the people of this continent, are not fearful of foreigners, because most of us were once foreigners. I say this to you as the son of immigrants, knowing that so many of you are also descended from immigrants."

"On this continent, too, thousands of persons are led to travel north in search of a better life for themselves and for their loved ones, in search of greater opportunities. Is this not what we want for our own children? We must not be taken aback by their numbers, but rather view them as persons, seeing their faces and listening to their stories, trying to respond as best we can to their situation."

DEATH PENALTY
"Recently my brother bishops here in the United States renewed their call for the abolition of the death penalty. Not only do I support them, but I also offer encouragement to all those who are convinced that a just and necessary punishment must never exclude the dimension of hope and the goal of rehabilitation."

ARMS TRADE
"Why are deadly weapons being sold to those who plan to inflict untold suffering on individuals and society? Sadly, the answer, as we all know, is simply for money: money that is drenched in blood, often innocent blood. In the face of this shameful and culpable silence, it is our duty to confront the problem and to stop the arms trade."

FAMILY
"I cannot hide my concern for the family, which is threatened, perhaps as never before, from within and without. Fundamental relationships are being called into question, as is the very basis of marriage and the family. I can only reiterate the importance and, above all, the richness and the beauty of family life."

POLITICS
"A good political leader is one who, with the interests of all in mind, seizes the moment in a spirit of openness and pragmatism. A good political leader always opts to initiate processes rather than possessing spaces."
link_name: This is what Pope Francis said to Congress this morning

status_message:
Another sign of a strengthening El Niño?  The tens of thousands of tiny red crabs invading the Channel Islands.  These types of crustaceans, pelagic red crabs, are usually found in Mexico's warm waters. But as the sea temperatures increase, the crabs follow the pockets of warm water and move north.

"This is definitely associated with El Niño."  http://lat.ms/1i7W7Xl

While researching sea lions for two months on San Miguel Island, one of the eight Channel Islands, biologist Jeff Harris noticed the crabs were marooning more than once a week.  "This is very important because the water is already very warm and it is said that the El Niño is still on its way. This could be a record event."

Video: Jeff Harris/Channel Islands National Park
link_name: Watch thousands of tiny red crabs invade Channel Islands

status_message:
RIP Amelia Boynton Robinson, a matriarch of the civil rights movement, who died yesterday at 104. 

She never became a household name, but the grainy photos of her crumpled on the side of the road in Selma, Ala., after being tear-gassed and beaten by state troopers came to be one of the most searing images of America's civil rights struggle.

Though she was clubbed, gassed and left splayed along the road in the first attempt to cross the Edmund Pettus Bridge, Boynton Robinson's resolve to fight for change only seemed to deepen.

She was invited later that year to the White House when President Johnson signed the Voting Rights Act. She became the first black woman to run for Congress in Alabama.

And in March — 50 years after the violence in Selma — she crossed the span again, this time in a wheelchair and pushed along by President Obama.

http://lat.ms/1NXEqU5

Photo: Jacquelyn Martin / AP

status_message:
The National Guard was supposed to be different from America's all-volunteer Army. For decades, Guard units were chiefly mobilized to respond to natural disasters and other emergencies in their states. Guardsmen were "weekend warriors," training only a few days a month. Relatively few fought in Korea, Vietnam or the first Gulf War. That changed after Sept. 11, 2001. 

When they return, an invisible wall divides them and their families from those they grew up with -- and most Americans.

Read more at latimes.com/nationalguard
link_name: The war at home

Just past midnight on a Friday every month, the Standard hotel is where two worlds collide: hipsters who've stumbled into their latest alternative scene, and gay and transgender men and women carrying on the legacy of their elders in the ballroom community. 

But this ain't your grandmother's ballroom.

This brand of ballroom serves as a place of acceptance for participants who find themselves otherwise marginalized. Most are black or Latino, and they "walk," or compete, at events known as balls. Many belong to cliques known as "houses." Led by a mother or father figure, houses serve as families for their members, some of whom have cut ties with their biological kin.

Check out our story to learn more: http://lat.ms/1Fg9uib
link_name: Inside the underground world of ballroom

status_message:
After 53 years on the air, Sabado Gigante is finally coming to an end. How was it a part of your life?  Tell us in the comments below or on Twitter with #AdiosSabado.  

"We sat many Saturday nights in front of the TV in my mother-in-law's living room.  Mama Chole on her big floral couch, my kids snuggled around her eating Hershey Kisses from her fancy candy bowl as we watched "Sabado Gigante" with Don Francisco's baritone voice booming through her Monterey Park house. These were our inter-generational bonding moments. Mama Chole spoke very little English. My kids hardly spoke Spanish. But "Sabado Gigante" brought us together for some laughs, a good-old fashioned American family hour, Latino style. My husband and I cringed at the skits and scantily-clad dancers. But we were all together.  As Mama Chole aged and her hearing went, the "Sabado Gigante" volume grew uncomfortably loud. We still watched.  When she was bed-ridden, on went "Sabado Gigante" on the living room television, even though there was no one on the couch anymore. Every so often, I still catch my husband holed up in our den watching the show alone."  

-- LA Times national desk editor, Stephanie Chavez

More: http://lat.ms/1HAMEAM
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
"They came with horses," Amelia Boynton Robinson recalled. "They came with nightsticks." On March 7, 1965, Alabama state troopers blocked civil rights demonstrators who had just crossed the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma. Boynton Robinson, then a middle-aged black woman, was tear-gassed and beaten and slumped unconscious on the side of the road. The troopers attacked the marchers in events that became known as "Bloody Sunday." 

Learn more about the woman now called "Queen Mother" and join us for a look back at the historical Civil Rights Movement and a look ahead at the modern movement 50 years after Selma at latimes.com/selma.

Not all cookies are created equally. Thin Mints, for example, look and taste different depending on what side of the great Girl Scout cookie divide you fall. Mansplaining meets the lady lecture: Over-explaining is everywhere, and it's not gender specific, argues Meghan Daum in Los Angeles Times Opinion.

"The reality is that 'splaining is everywhere, and it's ultimately not gender specific. There's the gymsplainer, who interrupts your workout to offer unwanted tips about proper use of the abdominal trainer. There's the foodsplainer, who won't shut up about artisanal this and farm-to-table that. And I hardly need to mention the momsplainer, who assumes her particular parenting strategies are so uniquely effective that it would be downright ungenerous not to impart them on the playground as though she were delivering a TED talk."
link_name: Mansplaining? Windbags come in both genders

"As we embark on the seventh year since the historic collapse of the Lehman Bros. investment bank, it's clear we haven't fixed what broke the economy in 2008. Big banks still control Congress. Wall Street does what America wants it to -- lend American families money they can't afford to pay back. Fixing Wall Street is easy. But then we would have to fix the problems that Wall Street's machinations mask. And that's hard." 

(via Los Angeles Times Opinion)

In 1923, Cecil B. DeMille built an elaborate set for his film "The Ten Commandments." Twenty-one giant sphinxes lined a path to an 800-foot-wide temple. Legend has it that after the filming was done, the set was too expensive to move and too valuable to leave for rival filmmakers to poach — so DeMille had it pushed into a trench and buried. 

This week, archaeologists excavated a plaster sphinx from what has now been dubbed the Lost City of DeMille.
link_name: Archaeologists unearth a DeMille sphinx

status_message: Since 2011, L.A. has stepped up its budgeted annual spending to replace water mains from $82 million to $112 million, according to the mayor's office. But even with the increased funding, the city is replacing its water mains at a rate of about once every 300 years. This year, officials aim to reduce that number to once every 250 years with existing funding, but speeding up upgrades to once a century could take billions of dollars more in investment — and much of it would need to come from ratepayers, a top DWP executive says.
link_name: Broken Sunset Boulevard water pipe was badly worn, DWP tells council

status_message:
In California, residential electricity prices shot up 30% between 2006 and 2012, adjusted for inflation, according to Energy Department figures. 

And a recent study predicts the cost of electricity in California could jump 47% over the next 16 years, in part because of the state's shift toward more expensive renewable energy.
link_name: U.S. electricity prices may be going up for good

status_message: "Climbing Everest is a luxury undertaken only by those with $30,000 to $100,000 to spend on what most of us would consider a nonessential trip," writes Karin Klein in Los Angeles Times Opinion. "For now, any team that insists on going ahead with the climb must know that it's being widely viewed as a group of rather spoiled, privileged brats. It is disappointing, sure, to have prepared, trained, hired, reserved and then have the whole thing fall apart. But it's not crucial to fulfill plans for a recreational climb. For the Sherpas, it's a matter of life and death."
link_name: The underpaid and too-dangerous lives of Everest's Sherpa guides

The story of Raymond "Shrimp Boy" Chow reads like a movie script:

Our Classic Hollywood | Los Angeles Times page is wishing a very happy birthday to Kim Novak, who was born on this date in 1933. When she got her start, Columbia Pictures' iron-willed studio chief Harry Cohn hoped his beautiful starlet would help quell any rebellion by Rita Hayworth, the studio's leading love goddess, and rival Marilyn Monroe, who worked across town at Fox. If you have memories of a place that stretch over a lifetime — from when you were a kid there to when you brought your kids and then their kids — it's hard to go back and see it empty and unloved, the flowers unwatered and dead, dust coating the floors and the benches.

It all happened so quickly at Hollywood Park, where thoroughbreds last thundered down the track just a month ago. Now, with that day's racing slips still scattered about the stands, everything that can be removed is being sold off: the ticket booths, the Jumbotron, the jockeys' impossibly small, narrow bunk beds.

Click through to read the rest of Los Angeles Times City Beat's last look at the 75-year-old racetrack:

status_message:
Harold Russell, born on this date 100 years ago, is the only person to win two Oscars for the same role. Russell, who lost both hands in a training accident during WWII, was awarded a special Oscar in 1947 for his performance in "The Best Years of Our Lives." He then beat out veteran actors Charles Coburn, Clifton Webb and Claude Rains for best supporting actor honors.

But he knew a long career in the movies was unlikely.

"Wyler told me I should go back to college, because there wasn't much call for a guy with no hands in the motion picture industry," Russell said.

He made news late in life for selling his best supporting Oscar, which he auctioned to put money in the bank for his family. Russell said he'd never sell the special award because it honored all veterans. He died in 2002 at the age of 88.

status_message:
Our Classic Hollywood | Los Angeles Times page is remembering Ricardo Montalban who was born on this date in 1920 in Mexico City.  

If you're a fan of vintage stars and films like our Classic Hollywood page to get coverage delivered to your news stream: https://www.facebook.com/ClassicHollywoodLAT

To many Montalban remains the mysterious Mr. Roarke of "Fantasy Island," a role that made him a household name for new generations of fans in the 1970s and 1980s. 

Montalban was already a star of Mexican movies in the 1940s when MGM cast him as a bullfighter opposite Esther Williams in "Fiesta" and put him under contract. Within the entertainment industry, he was widely respected for his efforts to create opportunities for Latinos, although he and others believed that his activism hurt his career. 

Here he is in a 1952 Times staff photo with his wife Georgiana and the youngest of their four children, Victor. He and Georgiana, who was Loretta Young's sister, were married in 1944 and together until her death in 2007. He passed away two years later at the age of 88.
link_name: Classic Hollywood

status_message:
Sessue Hayakawa, who died on this date in 1973, is being remembered today on our Classic Hollywood | Los Angeles Times page. 

Best known now for his Oscar-nominated role the camp commander in "The Bridge on the River Kwai" (1957), he was one of the great film idols of the early motion picture days and the highest-priced actor in films for a while. 

Hayakawa entered motion pictures in 1913, a year after graduating from the University of Chicago with a degree in political economy. His salary rose astronomically — from $150 a week to $1,000 a week to $7,500 a week. The public flocked to his pictures, "The Cheat," "The Tong Man," "An Arabian Knight." He is pictured here with Anna May Wong in 1931's "Daughter of the Dragon" courtesy of the UCLA Film and Television Archive.

Suddenly, from behind, we heard a thud. We turned to see that the Mercedes driver had done a U-turn, only to pull directly into the path of a cyclist. The bike and rider were now crumpled on the pavement. And what did the driver do? That's right: Jumping out of his car, he shrieked at the fallen biker: 'Look what you've done to my car!' "
link_name: L.A. as a bike-friendly place? Forget it. It's too dangerous.

status_message:
In August, Leon Logothetis departed from L.A. for "a trip around the world relying on the kindness of strangers. I have taken with me no money. I have no place to stay and no food. I also have no way to cross two oceans. All I have is my trusty bike and a firm belief in the generosity of the human spirit." 

So far, his trip has taken him as far as Istanbul and has included stops with ranchers in Nebraska, a homeless man in Pittsburgh, musicians from Benin in France, a former Bosnian soldier in Sarajevo and more. You can follow his journey with Los Angeles Times Travel's interactive map: http://lat.ms/1ezZWxc

Upset that the fiscal stalemate in Washington is threatening the global economy, China called for the U.S. dollar to be replaced as the international reserve currency as well as for broader steps to create a "de-Americanized world."

China also called for an end to the "pernicious impasse" in the U.S. over the raising the debt limit and ending the partial government shutdown, saying the world needed another reserve currency so nations could protect themselves "from the spillover of the intensifying domestic political turmoil in the United States."

Do you agree?

Our Classic Hollywood | Los Angeles Times page is remembering Carole Lombard, who was born on this date in 1908.

Are you fan of vintage Hollywood films and stars? Like our Classic Hollywood page to get coverage delivered to your stream: https://www.facebook.com/ClassicHollywoodLAT

Lombard was one of the best-loved stars of her era when she died at 33, a month after the U.S. entered World War II. She'd gone home to Indiana for a war bond rally and was flying back early to surprise her husband, Clark Gable, when her plane crashed outside of Las Vegas on Jan. 16, 1942 

She's pictured here in 1936 when she went to court in L.A. to change her name from Jane Peters Powell (the Powell was from her recently dissolved marriage to the actor William Powell.) Photo appears in the book, "High Exposure: Hollywood Lives– Found Photos from the Archives of the Los Angeles Times."

Our colleagues on the Classic Hollywood | Los Angeles Times page are wishing a happy birthday to French actress Brigitte Bardot, who turns 79 today. She is pictured here in a shot from the 1963 film "Contempt" (Courtesy of Rialto Pictures)

A 1972 L.A. Times Q&A with Bardot -- who had debuted 20 years earlier -- noted she had "arrived on the world cinema scene and was promptly dubbed the sex kitten." At the time of the conversation she was almost 38, the age at which she largely dropped out of view. Bardot said then "if you have no private life it is impossible to be really happy. There is a French proverb: To live happy, to live hidden. Where can Brigitte Bardot hide?"

status_message:
The San Diego County clerk filed a petition Friday afternoon asking the California Supreme Court to halt same-sex  marriages. The weddings resumed on June 28, two days after the U.S. Supreme Court effectively allowed a lower-ruling against Proposition 8 to become law.

The petition argues that the state does not have the right to order counties to perform same-sex marriages because the question of Proposition 8's legality is still before the courts.

In response, state Atty. Gen. Kamala D. Harris  said in a statement Friday that the county had offered "no new arguments" that could deny same-sex couples the right to marry.  "All 58 counties [must] perform same-sex marriages. No exceptions," Harris wrote.

Making a surprise appearance in the White House briefing room, President Obama reflected on his own experience with bias and racial profiling, and sought to explain why the African-American community was outraged over the case.
link_name: Obama reflects on race, says 'Trayvon Martin could have been me'

Here's a little post-workout downer for you: 

In more than two-thirds of the nation's counties – including some of the most unhealthy – men and women became more physically active over the last decade, according to data published Wednesday. But these improvements have done little to reduce obesity, researchers at the University of Washington's Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation concluded.

Many health experts believe that changing diet may do more to bring those numbers down than increasing exercise.
link_name: Americans exercise more, but are still not losing much weight

status_message:
Patrick Webster, with wife, Susie Martin, reflected on the flag that his father, Coast Guard Lt. Charles William Webster, brought home from World War II. 

The flag flew on a cutter that was part of Rescue Flotilla One, which saved more than 400 men off the beaches of Normandy during the D-day invasion in 1944.

Patrick recalled difficult memories his father shared, including his efforts to rescue a nurse from a bombed hospital ship. The young lieutenant was among the first on the scene and plunged into the water, but he couldn't reach the nurse in time. It haunted him the rest of this life.

Read more: http://lat.ms/10WLcjH

Photo: Gary Friedman / Los Angeles Times

The FBI has released images of two men who are suspects in the Boston Marathon bombings. The agency released photographs and video of the men and asked for the public's help in identifying them.

The images, which show the men in the vicinity of the attack, are the first to be made public by investigators.

The FBI has also found what it believes to be the detonation system for the bombs -- a circuit board and parts from a toy remote-control vehicle, a counter-terrorism official told the L.A. Times.

EDITORIAL: There are, in increasingly frightening numbers, cells of angry men in the United States preparing for combat with the U.S. government. They are usually heavily armed, blinded by an intractable hatred, often motivated by religious zeal.

status_message:
A new fad has gotten off the ground, literally, in Russia. Skywalkers -- or roofers, as they proudly call themselves -- climb a skyscraper, a construction crane, a tall monument, a tower or a bridge. When they get to the top, they balance themselves — sometimes on the tiniest of ledges — and take a lurch-in-the-stomach picture, like this one, of the view hundreds of feet below. Then they post it on the Internet.

"Human problems seem insignificant when you are hanging out on a star," said Artyom Lakhtionov, 19, a college photography student. "Even traffic jams that paralyze your life down there don't seem so hopeless. Read more: http://lat.ms/X9YmZl

status_message: The annual rush to shop this holiday season got underway in earnest on Thanksgiving as retailers began putting out their Black Friday specials early, and crowds showed up to check out the bargains. Many retailers – including Wal-Mart, Sears and Toys"R"Us – were trying to get a jump on the traditional start to the holiday shopping season by moving their opening times to as early as 8 p.m. on Turkey Day. The National Retail Federation said that 147 million shoppers are expected this weekend and more for online specials by Cyber Monday. status_message:
The LAFD's 911 dis­patch­ers rarely call for help from the neigh­bor­ing county Fire De­part­ment, even when county res­cuers are closer to emergencies near the jagged city border, ac­cord­ing to a Times ana­lys­is. 

In the case of Steph­anie Hooks, three county sta­tions were closer than the LAFD fire­houses that sent help. Her husband, Alvin Hooks, left, their daughter, Alnisha, 20, and mother- in-law Catherine Green, 72, waited for 10 minutes and 30 seconds for LAFD paramedics to arrive after Stephanie suffered cardiac arrest. She later died.

Learn more by reading The Times investigation. http://lat.ms/lafdborders

status_message: The space shuttle Endeavour is on its way from Los Angeles International Airport to the California Science Center in Exposition Park. The 12-mile route, which includes major thoroughfares such as Manchester, Crenshaw and Martin Luther King Jr. boulevards, looks radically different than it did months ago. Power lines have been lifted and trees have been removed. Nearly 2,700 steel plates were placed on streets to better distribute Endeavour's weight and protect the century-old infrastructure underneath. For more: http://lat.ms/P0z78c.
link_name: Endeavour's two-day L.A. journey

As L.A. readies for Endeavour's two-day journey to Exposition Park starting Friday, Los Angeles Times Photography, Video and Multimedia reminds us of another hefty move ... in June 1946.

The H-4 Hercules, a.k.a. Spruce Goose, was originally built in sections by Hughes Aircraft in Culver City. In June 1946, the wings, hull and other sections were transported to Terminal Island in Long Beach. The journey took two days, as movers traveled at 2 mph. The aircraft was assembled in Long Beach and flown in 1947. Read more in Framework: http://lat.ms/OUBNsL.

status_message:
Before Jayden David turned 5, he had tried a dozen powerful medications to tame a rare form of epilepsy. The side effects were devastating.

Then one day, Jason David, Jayden's father, said he heard about a teenager who was expelled from school for using marijuana to help control seizures. So began the pair's journey into California's medical cannabis culture.

And it's worked.

But now a U.S. crackdown on pot shops threatens David's supply of the medicinal solution.

The entire story and accompanying video are here: http://lat.ms/TQ7Lag. Framework, our photo and multimedia blog, also has a photo slideshow: http://lat.ms/RX4Uu9.

Breaking: U.S. defeats Japan to win women's soccer gold medal        

Two goals by Carli Lloyd and a late diving save by goalkeeper Hope Solo gave the U.S. women's soccer team a 2-1 victory over Japan and its third consecutive Olympic gold medal in the sport.

Lloyd had given the Americans a 2-0 lead before they surrendered a goal and then withstood several scoring efforts by Japan. The victory avenged a defeat to Japan in the World Cup last summer.

(via Los Angeles Times Sports)

status_message:
From the archives (Feb. 27, 1930): Dr. Karl T. Waugh conducts a psychogalvanoscope test on actress Dorothy Sebastian while others look on at MGM Studios. Standing left to right are Capt. Humphrey Read, who was assisting with the test, and Hollywood figures Hedda Hopper, Buster Keaton, Pauline Garon, Colleen Smith and Gwen Lee.

The Los Angeles Times reported the next morning:

An electric galvanoscope played strange tricks yesterday at the Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer studios when Dr. Karl T. Waugh, dean of psychology at the University of Southern California, measured the emotions of stars and players with the psychogalvanoscope, new device of science. The emotional impulses were gauged in terms of vacillation of the needle of the intricate but simple-looking machine.

Read more on Los Angeles Times Photography, Video and Multimedia's Framework blog: http://lat.ms/ME87N0
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
"Passing the Affordable Care Act was the greatest single step in generations toward ensuring access to affordable, quality healthcare for every person in America, regardless of where they live, how much money they make," Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid said. "I'm happy and I'm pleased the Supreme Court put the rule of law ahead of partisanship."

House Speaker John A. Boehner (R-Ohio) – and tea party groups -- vowed to press forward on efforts to repeal the law.

"Today's ruling underscores the urgency of repealing this harmful law in its entirety," Boehner said. "Republicans stand ready to work with a president who will listen to the people and will not repeat the mistakes that gave our country Obamacare."
link_name: Dems 'ecstatic,' GOP vows fight as court upholds healthcare law

From the archives (Jan. 27, 1936)

The original caption read: Passenger Engine No. 7856 of the Union Pacific rolled into the Los Angeles shops for a new set of tires. Roepke, mechanical supervisor, second from right, signals crane operator while J.H. On Feb. 15, 1953, The Times published this reader-submitted 1902 photo of downtown Los Angeles. The first few paragraphs of the accompanying story:

Downtown Los Angeles of 51 years ago -- an era when a four-story building ranked as a skyscraper -- is illustrated in a photograph received yesterday by The Times.

Mrs. Glenn Randolph Schreiner of Indianapolis, sent it after reading a copy of the Times Midwinter Edition.

"Looking at the pictures of your beautiful modern buildings," Mrs. Schreiner wrote,"I remembered a picture mailed to me years ago by an uncle who was working in your city at the time."

status_message:
"If I should stay I only be in your way," sings Houston in the opening bars of "I Will Always Love You," minus any instrumentation, as if into an abyss of loneliness. "So I'll go, but I know I'll think of you every step of the way." 

If you haven't heard it in a while, go back and listen, and wonder at Houston's pure tone, one that at its peak could not only hit a note and gracefully sustain it, but inject it with just enough flair and nuance to reinforce her control without pressing the point.
link_name: Whitney Houston: Voice for the ages tarnished by addictions

status_message:
Today in history: Hitler becomes German chancellor.

Here are the first two paragraphs of the Associated Press report that led the next day's Times:


BERLIN, Jan. 30 (AP) – Adolf Hitler achieved his long-sought goal – the Chancellorship of the Reich – today, and Nationalist Germany was thrown into a paroxysm of joy at the union of President von Hindenburg and the Nazi leader in a common effort to pull the fatherland out of the mire.

Hitler, having at last attained the coveted goal, must now show whether the Messiah-like hopes of 13,000,000 Germans in his statesmanship are justified.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
The Los Angeles Times will begin hosting free-to-the-public, monthly lunchtime mini-tours next week in its reopened, iconic 1935 Art Deco Globe Lobby.

The tours, called Thursdays @ The Globe, will feature meet-and-greet sessions with Times reporters, columnists, photojournalists, editors or executives.

The inaugural tour will be from noon to 1 p.m. Thursday, Nov. 17. 

The second tour, on Dec. 8, will feature award-winning Times photographer Mark Boster, who will sign copies of his new book, "Four Seasons in Yosemite."

Reservations will go fast: http://thursdaysattheglobe.eventbrite.com/

Like your favorites; later today we'll post the real caption.

UPDATE (the actual caption) : Two Labradors sit on their hind legs after being worshiped by their trainers at Nepal's central police dog training school on the dog worship day of the Tihar festival. The Tihar festival is the second major festival for Nepalese Hindus. During the festival, people worship crows, considered to be messengers of human beings; cows, considered incarnations of lord Laxmi, god of wealth; and dogs, repaying the love towards man's "best friend." EPA photo by Narendra Shrestha

From our archives: This week in 1953, Lucille Ball held a news conference to explain why she joined the Community Party in 1936.

From the Page 1 Times story: "Miss Ball, the red-haired star of TV's "I Love Lucy" said she was confident the current stir over her registration as a Communist in 1936 would not damage her career."

"Hurt me?" she said. "I have more faith in the American people than that. I think any time you give the American people the truth they're with you." …

Allene Kim and Shereen Lavi wanted us to ask RonArtest15 if he would ever go on "Dancing with the Stars". So we did.  

"I want to go but I would want to lose in the first round," Artest told Laker blogger Mark Medina Thursday. Naturally, Medina asked why on Earth would Artest want to lose so early?

"I wouldn't want to put my hips in the situation where I look like Rick Fox," Artest said of the former Lakers forward who had performed (pretty well) on the ABC dance contest.

Go to the Lakers blog (lakersblog.latimes.com) later to see the entire interview of Artest where he discussed a hilarious episode when he was  recording with Dr. Dre the night the Lakers won last year's title, why he has stopped drinking, and whether or not he wants to retire as a Laker. 

His answers will surprise you.
